# .trivyignore — accepted vulnerabilities (the documented allowlist for the CI Trivy gate).
#
# Accepting a CVE is a *reviewed security decision*, not a silent mute — every entry MUST carry:
# why it's accepted, an owner, and an expiry. The gate runs with `ignore-unfixed: true`, so a CVE
# only reaches this file if a fix exists somewhere that we cannot yet pull in.
#
# Format: one vulnerability ID per line; blank lines and `#` comments ignored. The `exp:YYYY-MM-DD`
# suffix makes the suppression self-expire — at that date the gate re-flags the CVE, forcing a
# conscious re-review (so suppressions can't quietly live forever).

# CVE-2026-41254: HIGH in liblcms2-2 (Little-CMS colour-management lib) in the distroless base OS.
# Accepted (time-boxed) because: (1) a fix exists in Debian (2.14-2 -> 2.14-2+deb12u1) but NO rebuilt
# gcr.io/distroless/java21-debian12 image carrying it is published yet, so it cannot be fixed by a
# digest bump today (verified: the :nonroot tag digest is unchanged from the one we pin); (2) it is
# not reachable from Conduit — a webhook service that does no colour management / image decoding.
# Owner: @adeel  Reversal: delete this line (next scan re-flags it).
# Re-review at expiry: bump the distroless digest once a rebuilt image ships, then remove this line.
CVE-2026-41254 exp:2026-07-17
